AB  - The article is devoted to the phenomenon of “women's” opera, which has been actively developing over the last two decades in contemporary American musical theatre and is clearly evident in the works of American post-minimalist composers. The main features of modern American “women” opera are considered using the example of two works — As One (2014) by Laura Kaminsky for mezzo-soprano, baritone and string quartet located on the stage, and Song from the Uproar: The Lives and Deaths of Isabelle Eberhardt (2012) by Missy Mazzoli for mezzo-soprano, vocal quintet and instrumental ensemble. The operas are placed in the context of the musical and theatrical art of the USA of recent decades, saturated with feminist issues. The fundamental characteristics of opera works by women composers include: the image of the main character who goes beyond the boundaries of conventions established by society (often the central character is a famous historical figure, a creative person with a unique destiny); an appeal to traumatic life experience, to the problems of identity, self-knowledge, self-determination, spiritual freedom; a relevant interpretation of complex relationships with family and society; the predominance of the subjective principle, the introspective nature of the narrative, confessionality; reliance on documentary sources. The operas of Kaminsky and Mazzoli fit into the paradigm of postminimalist musical theatre: chamber opera, speech-type intonation of vocal parts, repetitive technique at the level of organization of verbal and musical material, rejection of a symphony orchestra in favor of an instrumental ensemble, multimedia means of expression. In Mazzoliis opera Songfrom the Uproar: The Lives and Deaths of Isabelle Eberhardt modern computer sound processing methods, sampling techniques, indie-rock style, and the active use of electronics play an important role. © (2025), (Saint Petersburg State University). All right reserved.
