AB  - This study examines the influence of cultural context on emotional expressiveness in vocal art based on a comparative analysis of chamber and opera performances in China and Ukraine. Drawing on musicological, psychological, and cultural perspectives, it analyses the characteristics of vocal aesthetics and interpretative approaches across national traditions. The Chinese vocal style is characterised by contemplative emotionality, expressed through restrained dynamics, subtle intonational changes, and smooth phrasing, grounded in the ideals of inner harmony and symbolic moderation. In contrast, the Ukrainian tradition reflects emotional openness and dramatic intensity, influenced by folk and liturgical heritage, as well as contemporary social experience. The results of the study show that both traditions translate emotions into culturally specific performance grammar, illustrating different but equally sophisticated strategies of affective communication. These results may be helpful for intercultural vocal pedagogy and for improving interpretative approaches in globalised performance contexts. © 2025, Universidade Federal de Goias. All rights reserved.
