AB  - The pervasive effects of climate change have permeated various facets of human life, presenting unique challenges to numerous industries, including the performing arts. Among the myriad of artists navigating this evolving landscape, opera singers stand out as a particularly vulnerable group, facing many challenges stemming from the intricate interplay between their craft and the changing environment. The choice to focus on opera singers in this article is a deliberate one, grounded in the researcher's specialised knowledge and understanding of this specific artistic domain. Therefore, this article seeks to assess the impact of climate change on opera singers' well-being in South Africa. This article used a qualitative research methodology and mostly relied on secondary sources. Accredited academic journals, published peer-reviewed journal articles, academic books, reliable academic websites, and reliable databases were the data sources used in this article. The researcher then analysed the data using the content analysis technique to generate empirical knowledge and pinpoint any gaps in the current understanding of the complex impact of climate change on the welfare of opera singers. The psychosocial stress theory was used to understand the complex nature of stress and its impacts on individuals' mental and physical well-being due to climate change. The findings of this article reveal that opera singers in South Africa grapple with a unique convergence of artistic expression and environmental variability, making them an ideal group for studying the effects of climate change on performing artists. In conclusion, this article has illuminated the profound impact of climate change on the well-being of opera singers in South Africa. © 2024 Adonis and Abbey Publishers Ltd. All rights reserved.
